  782: Second, aggregation defeats noise, not bias: signals are unbiased by
  783: construction, and a common-mode bias uncorrelated with quality
  784: (misinformation, expressive allocation) would not average out — only
  785: endogenous social-proof contamination was tested, and proved largely
  786: benign because visible funding progress is itself quality-correlated in a
  787: well-anchored system. Third, elicitation is non-strategic by assumption;
  788: in deployment, signal reporting becomes a gaming and clientelism surface,
  789: and the mechanics of open scope construction remain a gated design
  790: problem. Within those bounds, the finding points in a clear direction: the binding variable is not who holds the pen but how much
  791: dispersed information the scope-construction institution ingests.
  792: 
  793: The simulation also disciplines rhetoric — in both directions. Nothing in
  794: E1–E3 supports describing Core v0 allocation as "the wisdom of crowds":
  795: the honest description is *inspectable intermediation with a
  796: citizen-correctable default*, which the results show is both realistic and
  797: better than the salience-driven alternative that unstructured platforms
  798: converge to. And nothing in E1–E3 licenses the opposite reading — that
  799: central planning knowledge beats distributed knowledge — because they
  800: never modeled distributed knowledge; when E4 does, aggregation wins
  801: wherever its named preconditions hold. Both discourses lose their slogan;
  802: the design keeps its numbers.
  803: 
  804: *A fair, symmetric re-examination (E4-v4/v5).* This first-pass E4 gave the
  805: central a fixed inspection bandwidth and left citizen signals unbiased — two
  806: idealizations that, an adversarial review showed, tilt the comparison in the
  807: distributed arm's favor. A rebuilt model
  808: (`scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs`,
  809: `research/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier-results.txt`, `research/e4-v5-capture-design.md`)
  810: gives *both* institutions a symmetric friction in perceiving true value,
  811: including harm: the central attenuates perceived harm by a coefficient η (0 =
  812: blind to diffuse harm, 1 = a fully accountable planner), while the distributed
  813: reads true valuations but the diffusely harmed under-participate at a rate β
  814: (voice inequality). The result is not a multiplier but a frontier with a
  815: closed-form parity locus (`research/e4-analytical-backbone.md`): both
  816: institutions are biased estimators of the same Samuelson value T = S⁺ − S⁻,
  817: ranking projects by S⁺ − θ·S⁻ with θ_C = η and θ_D = 1 − β, so the distributed
  818: dominates exactly when its coefficient is closer to the true harm-weight of one
  819: — i.e. **β < 1 − η**. The simulation confirms the law (parity on the
  820: anti-diagonal η + β = 1) and quantifies the delivered-value degradation off it
  821: (rough parity to ~1.8× as a **distributed-to-central ratio** across the plausible
  822: box — this is D/C, not a fraction of the full-information benchmark). The advantage
  823: is thus a property of *including the harmed*, not of aggregation per se; it reaches
  824: parity along the anti-diagonal β = 1 − η and turns into a central win below it
  825: (β > 1 − η) — which absorbs the participation-bias objection into the model's own
  826: β axis rather than leaving it external. Neither
  827: extreme is assumed: η is *swept*, not fixed, and a low but non-zero η is a
  828: defended regime, not a premise. The diffuse-harm literature (Bastiat's unseen
  829: costs; Olson's asymmetric organization on contested issues; Wilson's
  830: client-politics quadrant; Scott's legibility) describes *when* diffuse costs go
  831: unrepresented — each read at its proper scope, not as a claim of global
  832: blindness — while the opposing thesis that political competition disciplines the
  833: centre toward efficiency (Wittman 1989) holds weakest in exactly that
  834: client-politics quadrant. Empirically, most *measured* procurement loss is
  835: passive — incompetence, not theft (Bandiera, Prat and Valletti 2009) —
  836: consistent with a low but non-zero η.
  837: 
  838: *Capture-resistance guards the advantage (E4-v5).* Modelling organized capture
  839: symmetrically — the review's hardest objection, applied in fairness to the
  840: central planner too — the asymmetry widens rather than closes. A group captures
  841: a low-value project only when its private rent exceeds acquisition cost plus the
  842: expected sanction (Becker 1968); with the deterrence asymmetry carried entirely
  843: by detection probability and acquisition scaling (the penalty held equal,
  844: conservatively), the status quo turns net-harmful at rents near 10% of project
  845: cost while the distributed threshold — floored by the equal-per-citizen wallet,
  846: which money can persuade but cannot buy — sits roughly ten times higher (closed
  847: form ρ(C) in the backbone note). Detection is a snowball p = 1 − (1 − q)^m, so
  848: its floor is an expected m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p_c) ≈ 0.1 reporters drawn from the
  849: transparent affected public — low, but this is a model-internal statement whose
  850: force depends entirely on the stipulated detection gap (central ~0.10 vs
  851: distributed ~1.0), not an empirical burden-of-proof: sensitivity analysis is
  852: decisive here — the distributed advantage narrows and can reverse if distributed
  853: detection is driven down toward ~0.3, so the claim is that organized recapture is
  854: harder under the distributed arm's transparency *given these parameters*, not that
  855: it is ruled out. This ties Finding
  856: 4 to the integrity layer of Finding 5: the same fiscalization that makes value
  857: arrive is what keeps the allocation advantage from being bought back by
  858: organized rents, so the two are a layer and its safeguard rather than
  859: independent multipliers. Every magnitude here is model-internal; the literature
  860: (Olson, Wilson, Scott, Bastiat; Becker, Becker and Stigler, Stokes,
  861: Dyck-Morse-Zingales; Ostrom's self-monitoring commons) defends the direction,
  862: the mechanism, and the sign of the asymmetry — not the numbers.
  863: 
  864: *Analytical backbone.* Three closed forms carry the weight, each verified against
  865: the simulation (`research/e4-analytical-backbone.md`); the runs then only confirm
  866: them and quantify the degradation off the clean cases. **(i) The parity law.**
  867: Writing each institution as a biased estimator that ranks projects by S⁺ − θ·S⁻,
  868: the central keeps θ_C = η of perceived harm and the distributed reveals
  869: θ_D = 1 − β (the participation rate cancels from the ranking); since the true
  870: harm-weight is one, the distributed arm delivers more true value **iff
  871: β < 1 − η**, parity on the anti-diagonal. A bias–variance reading would predict
  872: that on the parity line, where the bias cancels, the lower-variance estimator wins —
  873: the distributed's revelation noise is zero (a funder knows her own value), the
  874: central's proxy noise is not. The implemented simulation does **not** bear this out
  875: at the accountable corner: at (η = 1, β = 0) the measured ratio is **0.89× — a
  876: central win (D/C < 1)** — so the honest reading is the noise-free parity law
  877: β = 1 − η, and the bias–variance tilt toward the distributed is not supported there.
  878: **(ii) The capture
  879: threshold.** From rent > acquisition + P(detect)·penalty, the central's threshold
  880: λ\*_C = (k_c + p_c·f)/C falls toward zero as its detection shrinks, while the
  881: distributed's λ\*_D = k_d + p_d·f/C is *floored* by the equal-wallet acquisition
  882: term k_d; the resistance ratio ρ(C) = (k_d·C + p_d·f)/(k_c + p_c·f) ≈ 6–10×,
  883: rising in project cost. **(iii) The detection floor.** With snowball detection
  884: P = 1 − (1 − q)^m, beating a central rate p_c needs, in the small-*q* (Poisson)
  885: approximation (1 − q)^m ≈ e^{−m·q}, only an expected m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p_c) ≈ 0.1
  886: reporters — the exact Bernoulli condition is m ≥ ln(1 − p_c)/ln(1 − q), which
  887: depends on *m* and *q* separately, not only on their product. It is a
  888: model-internal detection floor under the stipulated parameters
  889: (sensitivity-dependent; see Finding 4), not an empirical burden-of-proof inversion.
  890: Three invariances bound the arbitrary-magnitudes worry — as properties of the
  891: noise-free, large-set *expectation*, not of every finite-sample run: the advantage
  892: is invariant to the units of value (scale); in expectation it depends on the
  893: voice-bias β rather than on the participation *level* (though in finite samples
  894: turnout changes sample size, sampling variance, and hence rankings and
  895: portfolios); and, because only the first moments S⁺, S⁻ enter the expected
  896: ranking, the Gaussian valuation draw is a convenience there rather than a
  897: load-bearing assumption (finite-sample tails and valuation shape can still move
  898: rankings). One honest boundary the runs mark: the parity law is the large-set
  899: limit; when a project's interested set is very small — a handful of people — the
  900: distributed's sampling variance dominates and a full-census central regains the
  901: edge. Two further boundaries are honest to state. The comparison is *static* — a
  902: single allocation round — whereas real harms surface over iterated cycles and
  903: feed back through elections and audit, so a persistently blind centre is the
  904: stress case, not an inevitability. And the distributed arm is *scored on the true
  905: value it reveals*, which would be circular were it not that the β voice-bias and
  906: the capture frictions make its revealed signal a biased, contestable estimate of
  907: that value rather than a definitional one.
  908: 
  909: *Positioning.* The first-best preference-aggregation mechanism —
  910: Vickrey–Clarke–Groves — is infeasible for public budgets (it is not
