  945: **Finding 5: delivered value, not allocation, is where the architecture
  946: earns its keep — and selection and delivery interact.** A fifth,
  947: pre-registered experiment (`research/e5-value-delivery-design.md`) adds
  948: the execution stage the first four omitted: executors with hidden types
  949: whose diversion decision follows Proposition 1's incentive condition,
  950: under an opaque delivery regime — a zero-control lower bound (low
  951: detection, unprotected advances, no recovery, no reputational memory),
  952: with parameters inside the empirically documented leakage band: 87% in
  953: Uganda's capitation grants (Reinikka and Svensson 2004), 24% in
  954: Indonesian roads (Olken 2007) — versus the verified regime built from
  955: Propositions 1-4 (milestone gating, retention, recovery, evidence-layer
  956: detection, and a reputational stake: a visible confirmed-diversion record
  957: that costs future selection by funders).
  958: Crossing delivery with the two E4 selection regimes yields a 2×2 whose
  959: main effects are two plain questions. Same projects, different control
  960: layer: the verified regime delivers +43% on identical portfolios
  961: (paired ΔV = 0.168 [0.143, 0.193]), and the zero-control regime's
  962: official completion overstates its real delivery by twenty-nine
  963: percentage points. Same control layer, different
  964: projects: social prioritization delivers +53-54% under either regime.
  965: The interaction is positive and significant (+0.085 [0.053, 0.117]): within
  966: this apparatus the two layers **interact rather than merely add**, yielding a
  967: **conditional zero-control scenario output of 2.19×** per unit of budget
  968: (0.859 vs 0.393) across direct-participation rates from 3% (the
  969: participatory-budgeting floor) to 40% (voting-scale). This compound is a
  970: model-internal factorial contrast, **not** a calibrated effect (see the
  971: quantitative-status note in Section 6 and the estimand contract). Two
  972: pre-registered predictions failed honestly.
  973: The expected dominance of delivery over selection did not hold at this
  974: scale — central selection at two hundred projects is near-random (E4),
  975: inflating the selection margin — so within this apparatus the robust pattern is
  976: the *interaction* of the two layers, not their ranking (the compound magnitude
  977: itself is retired as a calibrated effect; see Section 6). And the expected
  978: reputational cleansing never fired
  979: under the strong verification parameters, for the best possible reason:
  980: the incentive condition holds for every executor, so no one diverts and
  981: there is no one to exclude — deterrence pre-empts punishment, Becker's
  982: enforcement working ex ante. A labeled post-hoc sensitivity with weakened
  983: verification shows the second line of defense: partial deterrence,
  984: active detection, and an executor pool that measurably improves as
